"><sup>a</sup></lk><sup>, </sup><lk key="d.b.johnson@bangor.ac.uk" type="email"><sup>&REemail;</sup></lk></lnsm:aug></lnsm:p></lnv:AUTHORS><lnv:AFFILIATION><refpt id="implicit0"/><sup>a</sup> School of Biological Sciences, Bangor University, Bangor, LL57 2UW, UK</lnv:AFFILIATION><lnv:HISTORY><lnv:RECEIVED><lnsm:optionhead>Received </lnsm:optionhead>13 January 2011;&nbsp;</lnv:RECEIVED><group-separator> </group-separator><lnv:REVISED>revised 25 March 2011;&nbsp;</lnv:REVISED><group-separator> </group-separator><lnv:ACCEPT><lnsm:optionhead>accepted </lnsm:optionhead>18 April 2011.&nbsp;</lnv:ACCEPT><group-separator> </group-separator><lnv:PUBLISHED><lnsm:optionhead>Available online </lnsm:optionhead>28 April 2011.</lnv:PUBLISHED></lnv:HISTORY><lnv:PRIM-ABST><lnsm:optionhead><h l="1">Abstract</h></lnsm:optionhead><lnsm:abs><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0045"/><p>An empirical technique for the rapid assessment of active biomass of acidophilic microorganisms in pure cultures and in leach liquors from mineral bio-processing operations is described. The method is based on the measurement of ATP concentrations in test solutions, using commercially-available kits and a portable luminometer. The ATP contents of five Gram-negative biomining bacteria mineral-degrading acidophiles assayed varied from 0.87<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup> to 18<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>mol per cell in actively-growing cultures. Depletion of ferrous iron in cultures of a strain of <emph typestyle="it">Leptospirillum ferriphilum</emph> resulted in rapid mortality of the iron-oxidizing bacterium (denoted by decreasing numbers of plate isolates) and corresponding changes in ATP concentrations in culture aliquots. The technique was applied successfully to mineral leachates from stirred tank biomining operations, where it was shown to determine populations of active microorganisms in liquors where most of the cells present were not viable. The method is highly sensitive (detecting as few as 10<sup loc="post">3</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>acidophiles<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> of test solution) and would therefore have generic application in monitoring microbial populations in other types of biomining operations, such as heap bioreactors.</p></lnsm:view></lnsm:abs></lnv:PRIM-ABST><lnv:SPECIAL-ABST><lnsm:abs class="graphical"><lnsm:optionhead><h l="2">Research highlights</h></lnsm:optionhead><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0050"/><p>&#x25ba; A rapid empirical method for determining the total active biomass of acidophiles. &#x25ba; The method determines ATP concentrations and uses low-cost equipment and reagents. &#x25ba; The technique has been successfully applied for mineral leach liquors.</p></lnsm:view></lnsm:abs></lnv:SPECIAL-ABST><lnv:AUTHOR-KWDS><lnsm:kwdg language="EN" class="keyword"><emph typestyle="bf">Keywords: </emph><lnsm:kwd>Acidophiles</lnsm:kwd>; <lnsm:kwd><emph typestyle="it">Acidithiobacillus</emph></lnsm:kwd>; <lnsm:kwd>ATP</lnsm:kwd>; <lnsm:kwd>Biomining</lnsm:kwd>; <lnsm:kwd><emph typestyle="it">Leptospirillum</emph></lnsm:kwd>; <lnsm:kwd><emph typestyle="it">Sulfobacillus</emph></lnsm:kwd></lnsm:kwdg></lnv:AUTHOR-KWDS><lnv:ARTICLE-TOC><lnsm:optionhead><h l="1">Article Outline</h></lnsm:optionhead><l type="def"><li>1. <lk refid="s0005">Introduction</lk></li><li>2. <lk refid="s0010">Materials and methods</lk><l type="def"><li>2.1. <lk refid="s0015">Assay calibration and ATP-based assays of mineral leaching bacteria</lk></li><li>2.2. <lk refid="s0020">Changes in ATP contents in energy-depleted cultures of <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> BRGM1</lk></li><li>2.3. <lk refid="s0025">ATP assay of microbial biomass in commercial mineral leachates</lk></li></l></li><li>3. <lk refid="s0030">Results and discussion</lk></li><li><lk refid="ack001">Acknowledgements</lk></li><li><lk refid="bibl001">References</lk></li></l></lnv:ARTICLE-TOC><lnv:FIG-LIST><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0005"/><inl alt-width="219" alt-height="144" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-2" width="346" height="228" size="16647" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-1"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;1.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0005"/><lnsm:p>Relationship between light emission (relative light units; RLU) and amount of ATP assayed in test solutions prepared at pH 7 (&#x25a0;) and pH 2 (&#x25cf;).</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0010"/><inl alt-width="219" alt-height="148" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-4" width="337" height="228" size="18861" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-3"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;2.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0010"/><lnsm:p>Relationship between cell numbers of (&#x25cf;) <emph typestyle="it">A. ferrooxidans</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, (&#x25b2;) <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, and (&#x25a0;) <emph typestyle="it">S. benefaciens</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup> and ATP contents, in nonsubstrate-depleted cultures (R<sup loc="post">2</sup> values were &gt;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>0.99 in all cases).</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0015"/><inl alt-width="126" alt-height="163" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-6" width="374" height="484" size="32340" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-5"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;3.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0015"/><lnsm:p>Changes in numbers of total (&#x25cf;) and viable (&#x25cb;) cells of <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> BRGM1 during and following completion of ferrous iron oxidation (+), and comparative changes in culture ATP contents evaluated on a unit total cell (&#x25bc;) or viable cell (&#x2207;) basis.</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0020"/><inl alt-width="207" alt-height="164" 