ar="&#xd7;" align="char">1.6<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> (BRGM1)</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">1.8<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;19</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">Sb. benefaciens</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup></entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">3.6<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;18</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">At. caldus</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup></entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">5.0<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup></entry></row></tbody></tgroup></table></lnsm:tbl></lnv:TABLE-LIST><lnv:TEXT-1><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="s0005"/><h l="1">1. Introduction</h></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"/><refpt id="p0005"/><p>&#x201c;Biomining&#x201d; has developed into an important biotechnology since its inception as a method of extracting copper from run-of-mine ore in the late 1960s (<refpt id="bbb0015"/><lk refid="bb0015">Brierley, 2008</lk>). Large-scale dump and heap leaching of copper and polymetallic ores, and bio-oxidation of refractory gold concentrates in stirred tanks (each typically &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>1,000<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>m<sup loc="post">3</sup>) is practiced in many different countries worldwide (<refpt id="bbb0025"/><lk refid="bb0025">&#x5b;Donati and Sand, 2007&#x5d;</lk> and <refpt id="bbb0035"/><lk refid="bb0035">&#x5b;Johnson, 2010&#x5d;</lk>). The microorganisms that are found in stirred tank systems and, to a lesser extent, heap and dump operations, are predominantly acidophilic iron- and sulfur-oxidizing bacteria and archaea (reviewed in <refpt id="bbb0070"/><lk refid="bb0070">Rawlings and Johnson, 2007</lk>). Some of these (such as <emph typestyle="it">Leptospirillum</emph> spp. and <emph typestyle="it">Acidithiobacillus</emph> spp.) are obligate autotrophs, though others (e.g. <emph typestyle="it">Sulfobacillus</emph> spp. and <emph typestyle="it">Ferroplasma</emph> spp.) metabolize organic carbon (<refpt id="bbb0070"/><lk refid="bb0070">Rawlings and Johnson, 2007</lk>).</p><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0010"/><p>Various techniques have been used to quantify and identify mineral-oxidizing microorganisms, including classical microbiological approaches (e.g. plating on selective solid media and preliminary identification from colony morphologies; <refpt id="bbb0040"/><lk refid="bb0040">Johnson and Hallberg, 2007</lk>) and molecular techniques such as denaturing gradient gel electrophoresis (DGGE; <refpt id="bbb0020"/><lk refid="bb0020">Demergasso et al., 2005</lk>) and real time quantitative PCR (qPCR; <refpt id="bbb0075"/><lk refid="bb0075">Remonsellez et al., 2007</lk>). Drawbacks with such approaches are the time required to obtain results, and the fact that some techniques require skills and experience that might not be readily available. There would be considerable merit in having available at a biomine site an empirical, low-cost technique that could provide a rapid &#x201c;health check&#x201d; on the state of mineral bioleaching populations.</p></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0015"/><p>Measurement of ATP has been used widely to determine active biomass in soils, aquatic ecosystems and extreme environments (<refpt id="bbb0005"/><lk refid="bb0005">&#x5b;Atkinson et al., 2000&#x5d;</lk>, <refpt id="bbb0030"/><lk refid="bb0030">&#x5b;Eiland, 1983&#x5d;</lk> and <refpt id="bbb0055"/><lk refid="bb0055">&#x5b;Jorgensen et al., 1992&#x5d;</lk>). It has also been used to monitor the effect of molybdate on the acidophile &#x201c;<emph typestyle="it">Ferroplasma acidarmanus</emph>&#x201d; (<refpt id="bbb0010"/><lk refid="bb0010">Baumler et al., 2008</lk>). Advantages of measuring ATP are the ease by which it can be carried out using commercially-available kits and relatively inexpensive equipment (a luminometer), while the downsides include the fact that ATP measurements do not give information on the identity of organisms present in a sample and, being an enzyme-based technique, they are prone to inhibition by a variety of agents, including those (such as dissolved metals) that are usually present in mineral leach liquors at very high concentrations.</p></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0020"/><p>Here we describe an ATP-based protocol for determining active populations of mineral-degrading acidophilic bacteria, and the application of the technique to determine active biomass in commercial leach liquors.</p></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="s0010"/><h l="1">2. Materials and methods</h></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0025"/><p>The ATP bioluminescence assay kit used was obtained from Hygiena, (Watford, U.K.), marketed as the &#x201c;Contamination Control Kit&#x201d; (CCK-2). This comprises two solutions, one containing a mixture on non-ionic cell lysing agents and an ATPase inhibitor (reagent I), and the other luciferin and firefly luciferase (reagent II). The routine analysis involved placing 100<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#x3bc;l of test solution in a cuvette, addition (with mixing) in sequence 150<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#x3bc;l of reagent I, followed by 350<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#x3bc;l of reagent II, and recording resulting light emission (as relative light units; RLU) using a portable luminometer (<emph typestyle="it">systemSURE</emph>&#x2122;, Hygiena). Each test was carried out in triplicate and mean values recorded.</p></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="s0015"/><h l="2">2.1. Assay calibration and ATP-based assays of mineral leaching bacteria</h></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0030"/><p>An ATP stock solution (10<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>mM) was prepared by dissolving ATP (Sigma-Aldrich, U.K.) in autoclaved MilliQ-grade water (MQW; Millipore Inc, Billerica, MA). The stock solution was serially diluted with sterile MQW (pH &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>7, or acidified to pH 2.0) to give concentrations of ATP of between 10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;3</sup> and 10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;13</sup> M, and corresponding RLU values recorded.</p></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0035"/><p>A range of acidophilic iron- and sulfur-oxidizing bacteria, all of which have been identified in commercial mineral bio-processing operations (<refpt id="bbb0050"/><lk refid="bb0050">&#x5b;Johnson et al., 2008&#x5d;</lk> and <refpt id="bbb0065"/><lk refid="bb0065">&#x5b;Okibe et al., 2003&#x5d;</lk>), were screened for their ATP contents. These were: <emph typestyle="it">Acidithiobacillus ferrooxidans</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, <emph typestyle="it">Leptospirillum ferrooxidans</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, which were grown at 30<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#xb0;C, and <emph typestyle="it">Leptospirillum ferriphilum</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> (strain BRGM1) and <emph typestyle="it">Sulfobacillus benefaciens</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup> and <emph typestyle="it">Acidithiobacillus caldus</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, which were grown at 45<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#xb0;C. All of these were grown in a liquid medium (initial pH 2.0) containing 1% fine-grain (&lt;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>1<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>mm diameter) pyrite (<refpt id="bbb0080"/><lk refid="bb0080">Wakeman et al., 2008</lk>), except <emph typestyle="it">At. caldus</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup> which was grown in a liquid medium (initial pH 2.5) containing 2.5<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>mM potassium tetrathionate. When planktonic cell numbers had increased to &gt;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>1.0<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">8</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> (total cell counts; determined using a Thoma counting chamber and a Leitz Labolux phase contrast microscope at &#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>400 magnification), bacteria were harvested by centrifugation and resuspended in MQW (pH 2) to give 1.0<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">9</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>. This suspension was then serially diluted with pH 2 MQW to give between 10<sup loc="post">2</sup> and 10<sup loc="post">9</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>, and ATP concentrations in 100<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#x3bc;l aliquots determined.</p></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="s0020"/><h l="2">2.2. Changes in ATP contents in energy-depleted cultures of <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> BRGM1</h></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0040"/><p><emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> (strain BRGM1) was grown in 20<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>mM ferrous sulfate medium (pH 2.0), incubated, shaken, at 45<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#xb0;C. Samples were removed at regular intervals up to and beyond the completion of iron oxidation, and analyzed for total bacterial cells, viable bacterial numbers (plating onto iron overlay plates (<refpt id="bbb0040"/><lk refid="bb0040">Johnson and Hallberg, 2007</lk>), and concentrations of ATP and ferrous iron (using the ferrozine assay; <refpt id="bbb0060"/><lk refid="bb0060">Lovley and Phillips, 1987</lk>).</p></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="s0025"/><h l="2">2.3. ATP assay of microbial biomass in commercial mineral leachates</h></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0045"/><p>Four samples of mineral leachates from pilot-scale stirred tanks were obtained from Mintek (Randberg, South Africa); their mineral compositions and operational parameters of the stirred tanks are given in <refpt id="bt0005"/><lk refid="t0005">Table&#xa0;1</lk>. One ml of each sample was vortexed for 2<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>min (to aid detachment of cells from mineral particles), gently centrifuged (800<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/><emph typestyle="it">g</emph> for 20<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>s) to remove solid particles, and the cell-containing supernatant collected and centrifuged at 16,000<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/><emph typestyle="it">g</emph> for 5<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>min to pellet the microorganisms. Supernatants were discarded, cells were resuspended in 1<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml of pH 2 MQW, and 100<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>&#x3bc;l aliquots used for ATP measurements as described previously. Total cells present in the resuspended biomass were enumerated using a Thoma counting chamber, and viable acidophiles by plating onto a range of selective overlay media (<refpt id="bbb0040"/><lk refid="bb0040">Johnson and Hallberg, 2007</lk>).</p><lnsm:tbl loc="float"><refpt id="t0005"/><lnsm:tbllabel>Table&#xa0;1. </lnsm:tbllabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0030"/><lnsm:p>Stirred tank bioreactor samples (Mintek, South Africa).</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption><table rowsep="0" colsep="0" frame="topbot"><tgroup cols="8"><colspec colname="col1"/><colspec colname="col2"/><colspec colname="col3"/><colspec colname="col4"/><colspec colname="col5"/><colspec colname="col6"/><colspec colname="col7"/><colspec colname="col8"/><thead><row valign="top" rowsep="1"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left">Sample</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" align="left">Concentrate</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col3" align="left">T (&#xb0;C)</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col4" align="left">pH</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col5" align="left">Cu</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col6" align="left">Fe</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col7" align="left">Ni</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col8" align="left">Zn</entry></row></thead><tbody><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left">1</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" align="left">Cu&#x2013;Ni</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col3" char="." align="char">37</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col4" char="." align="char">1.6</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col5" char="." align="char">2</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col6" char="." align="char">45</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col7" char="." align="char">10</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col8" align="left">&#x2013;</entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left">2</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" align="left">Cu&#x2013;Ni</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col3" char="." align="char">45</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col4" char="." align="char">1.6</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col5" char="." align="char">2.5</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col6" char="." align="char">25</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col7" char="." align="char">9</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col8" align="left">&#x2013;</entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left">3</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" align="left">Chalcopyrite</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col3" char="." align="char">45</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col4" char="." align="char">1.6</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col5" char="." align="char">28</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col6" char="." align="char">29</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col7" align="left">&#x2013;</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col8" align="left">&#x2013;</entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left">4</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" align="left">Polymetallic (Cu, Fe, Zn, Ag, Pb)</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col3" char="." align="char">45</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col4" char="." align="char">1.7</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col5" char="." align="char">12</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col6" char="." align="char">8</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col7" align="left">&#x2013;</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col8" char="." align="char">4</entry></row></tbody></tgroup></table><lnsm:legend><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0035"/><lnsm:p>All metal concentrations are shown as g<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>l<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>; &#x2013; indicates concentrations of &lt;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>1<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>g<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>l<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>.</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:legend></lnsm:tbl></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="s0030"/><h l="1">3. Results and discussion</h></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0050"/><p>A log&#x2013;log plot of RLU vs. ATP concentrations gave a linear relationship within the range of 10&#x2013;30,000 RLU using either acidic or non-acidic ATP test solutions (<lk refid="f0005">Fig.&#xa0;1</lk>). The pH 2 test solutions had a lower RLU response (about one order of magnitude) than those at pH &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>7, though this was not considered to be a significant detraction and was compensated for by pragmatic advantages with using low pH liquors when assessing populations of acidophiles, such as avoidance of ferric iron hydrolysis and precipitation. In practice, test samples containing between 10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;15</sup> and 10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;11</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>mol of ATP (corresponding to between 10 and &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>10,000 RLU, using pH 2 test liquors) were measured routinely.</p><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0005"/><inl alt-width="219" alt-height="144" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-2" width="346" height="228" size="16647" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-1"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;1.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0005"/><lnsm:p>Relationship between light emission (relative light units; RLU) and amount of ATP assayed in test solutions prepared at pH 7 (&#x25a0;) and pH 2 (&#x25cf;).</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0055"/><p>Serial dilutions of cell suspensions of different species and strains of acidophilic bacteria gave proportional changes in measured ATP concentrations (<lk refid="f0010">Fig.&#xa0;2</lk>). From these data, the ATP content was calculated for each of the acidophilic bacteria under the culture conditions imposed (<refpt id="bt0010"/><lk refid="t0010">Table&#xa0;2</lk>). The five Gram-negative acidophiles (<emph typestyle="it">Acidithiobacillus</emph> and <emph typestyle="it">Leptospirillum</emph> spp.) contained similar amounts of ATP, ranging from 0.87 to 18<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>mol<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>cell<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>. These data suggested that the different species of iron- and sulfur-oxidizing acidophiles were all lysed effectively by reagent I of the assay kit. Active cultures of the only Gram-positive bacterium analyzed (<emph typestyle="it">Sb. benefaciens</emph>) contained significantly more ATP (360<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>mol<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>cell<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>) which can be attributed in part to the fact that cells of <emph typestyle="it">Sulfobacillus</emph> spp. tend to be much larger than those of <emph typestyle="it">Acidithiobacillus</emph> and <emph typestyle="it">Leptospirillum</emph>, but may also may be due to a greater &#x201c;energy charge&#x201d; in the mixotrophic than in the autotrophic acidophiles. Overall, the ATP assay was sensitive enough to detect 10<sup loc="post">3</sup> to 10<sup loc="post">5</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>, depending on bacterial species.</p><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0010"/><inl alt-width="219" alt-height="148" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-4" width="337" height="228" size="18861" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-3"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;2.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0010"/><lnsm:p>Relationship between cell numbers of (&#x25cf;) <emph typestyle="it">A. ferrooxidans</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, (&#x25b2;) <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup>, and (&#x25a0;) <emph typestyle="it">S. benefaciens</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup> and ATP contents, in nonsubstrate-depleted cultures (R<sup loc="post">2</sup> values were &gt;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>0.99 in all cases).</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig><lnsm:tbl loc="float"><refpt id="t0010"/><lnsm:tbllabel>Table&#xa0;2. </lnsm:tbllabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0040"/><lnsm:p>Calculated ATP contents (mol<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>cell<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>) in nonsubstrate-depleted cultures of acidophilic bacteria.</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption><table rowsep="0" colsep="0" frame="topbot"><tgroup cols="2"><colspec colname="col1"/><colspec colname="col2"/><thead><row valign="top" rowsep="1"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left">Bacteria</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" align="left">ATP (mol/cell)</entry></row></thead><tbody><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">At. ferrooxidans</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup></entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">7.9<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">L. ferrooxidans</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup></entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">8.7<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;21</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup></entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">1.6<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> (BRGM1)</entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">1.8<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;19</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">Sb. benefaciens</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup></entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">3.6<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;18</sup></entry></row><row valign="top"><entry valign="center" colname="col1" align="left"><emph typestyle="it">At. caldus</emph><sup loc="post">T</sup></entry><entry valign="center" colname="col2" char="&#xd7;" align="char">5.0<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;20</sup></entry></row></tbody></tgroup></table></lnsm:tbl></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0060"/><p>When grown in ferrous iron liquid medium, numbers of both total and viable <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> BRGM1 increased during the period of iron oxidation, but decreased once this energy source had been dissipated, rapidly so in the case of viable cells (<lk refid="f0015">Fig.&#xa0;3</lk>). Similar results have previously been reported for the related species, <emph typestyle="it">L. ferrooxidans</emph> (<refpt id="bbb0045"/><lk refid="bb0045">Johnson et al., 2004</lk>). ATP contents of viable cells remained fairly stable at about 10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;19</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>mol<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>cell<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> during and beyond the phase of active growth, which was similar to the value obtained with pyrite-grown cultures, where the substrate was not depleted. In contrast, when measured against total cell numbers, ATP contents per unit cell declined rapidly after the ferrous iron had been oxidized, falling to about 1% of the maximum value found during exponential growth (<lk refid="f0015">Fig.&#xa0;3</lk>). These data confirmed that ATP measurements are appropriate for assessing the biomass of viable, active acidophilic bacteria. Alternative biomass measurements, such as protein determinations, do not discriminate between active and moribund cells, and therefore can overestimate active biomass, if used alone.</p><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0015"/><inl alt-width="126" alt-height="163" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-6" width="374" height="484" size="32340" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-5"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;3.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0015"/><lnsm:p>Changes in numbers of total (&#x25cf;) and viable (&#x25cb;) cells of <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> BRGM1 during and following completion of ferrous iron oxidation (+), and comparative changes in culture ATP contents evaluated on a unit total cell (&#x25bc;) or viable cell (&#x2207;) basis.</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0065"/><p>ATP concentrations could be determined in all four commercial samples tested, though this was only possible when solid particles and soluble metals present in the mineral leachates were removed, as these severely inhibited the enzymatic assay. This was achieved either by serial dilution of cell suspensions or by repeated washing (between 2 and 4 times) with acidic MQW. While total counts of microorganisms in the leach samples ranged between &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>10<sup loc="post">9</sup> and 10<sup loc="post">10</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>, viable numbers in two samples analyzed were far fewer (6<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">5</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> in sample 3, and 4<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">7</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> in sample 4; <lk refid="f0020">Fig.&#xa0;4</lk>). Identification of isolates, based on colony and cellular morphologies (<refpt id="bbb0065"/><lk refid="bb0065">Okibe et al., 2003</lk>) showed that <emph typestyle="it">At. caldus</emph> was the dominant acidophile present (in terms of numbers) in sample 3, and that significant numbers of <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> and a <emph typestyle="it">Ferroplasma</emph>-like archaeon were also present, whereas in sample 4, <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> accounted for 87% of the cultivatable microbial community (<lk refid="f0025">Fig.&#xa0;5</lk>). No archaea were isolated from sample 4, though a <emph typestyle="it">Sulfobacillus</emph>-like <emph typestyle="it">Firmicute</emph> (which, like <emph typestyle="it">Ferroplasma</emph>, can metabolize organic carbon originating from the autotrophic acidophiles) and <emph typestyle="it">At. caldus</emph> were detected (at 6% and 7% of the total viable population, respectively). ATP concentrations showed similar trends to those of total numbers of microorganisms in the mineral leachates though were notably depressed in sample 3 (<lk refid="f0020">Fig.&#xa0;4</lk>). However, when converted to equivalent biomass (assuming an average ATP content of &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>10<sup loc="post">&#x2212;19</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>mol ATP per acidophile; <refpt id="bt0010"/><lk refid="t0010">Table&#xa0;2</lk>) the values, which ranged from &#x7e;10<sup loc="post">7</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> (sample 3) to 10<sup loc="post">8</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> (sample 1) were over two orders of magnitude smaller than those of total microbial counts. In contrast, ATP concentrations were closely equated with plate counts of acidophilic isolates for sample 4 (estimated as &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>6<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">7</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> from ATP measurements, and &#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>4<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">7</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup> for plate counts. With sample 3, ATP-equivalent counts (&#x7e;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.10"/>1<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">7</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>active cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>) were somewhat greater than those of plate counts (6<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>&#xd7;<lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>10<sup loc="post">5</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>) possibly indicating that not all of the acidophiles present were isolated on the solid media used.</p><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0020"/><inl alt-width="207" alt-height="164" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-8" width="379" height="299" size="21491" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-7"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;4.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0020"/><lnsm:p>Total and viable numbers of microorganisms in mineral leachates, and corresponding ATP values (expressed as RLU); * not determined.</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig><lnsm:fig loc="float"><refpt id="f0025"/><inl alt-width="219" alt-height="161" alt-uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-B" width="332" height="245" size="13918" uoi="B6VBT-52R9DM4-2-9"/><lnsm:figlabel>Fig.&#xa0;5.&nbsp;</lnsm:figlabel><lnsm:caption><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="sp0025"/><lnsm:p>Viable (plate) counts of acidophilic bacteria and archaea in mineral leachates.</lnsm:p></lnsm:view></lnsm:caption></lnsm:fig></lnsm:view><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="p0070"/><p>The ATP protocol described can be used to obtain valuable information on the status of microbial populations in stirred tank mineral processing operations. Data are obtained within minutes of sampling. As illustrated in the present study, the vast majority of microorganisms in mineral leachates may be inactive (or dead), and therefore a technique, such as ATP measurements, that can discriminate between moribund and viable cells is essential for obtaining meaningful quantitative data on active populations. In a previous report (<refpt id="bbb0065"/><lk refid="bb0065">Okibe et al., 2003</lk>) numbers of viable acidophiles in leach liquors in a series of in-line stirred tank reactors were found to be between 10<sup loc="post">6</sup> and 10<sup loc="post">7</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>, which are similar values to those found in the current work. Perturbations in cultures (e.g. mass mortalities) can be detected by the ATP assay, as demonstrated with the pure culture of <emph typestyle="it">L. ferriphilum</emph> BRGM1, where most bacteria became non-viable soon after the energy source was depleted. Numbers of acidophiles are generally smaller in pregnant leach solutions (PLS) at heap leaching sites (typically 10<sup loc="post">3</sup> to 10<sup loc="post">6</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>; <refpt id="bbb0075"/><lk refid="bb0075">Remonsellez et al., 2007</lk>) than in stirred tank leachates. Although not tested in the present work, the ATP protocol described would also be appropriate for detecting perturbations in active microbial populations in PLS in heap operations, given that its lower sensitivity limit is about 10<sup loc="post">3</sup><lnsm:hsp sp="0.12"/>cells<lnsm:hsp sp="0.25"/>ml<sup loc="post">&#x2212;1</sup>.</p></lnsm:view></lnv:TEXT-1><lnv:ACKNOWLEDGE><refpt id="ack001"/><lnsm:optionhead><h l="1">Acknowledgements</h></lnsm:optionhead><p><lnsm:view type="all"/><refpt id="p0075"/></p><p>We are grateful to Dr. Mariekie Gericke (Mintek, South Africa) for supplying the mineral concentrates and the corresponding analytical data. This work was carried out in the frame of BioMinE (European project contract NMP1-CT-500329-1). The authors acknowledge the financial support given to this project by the <refpt id="gts0005"/><lnsm:grant-sponsor type="simple">European Commission</lnsm:grant-sponsor> under the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Development. We also wish to thank our various partners on the project for their contributions to the work reported in this paper. DBJ is grateful to the Royal Society (U.K.) for the award of an Industrial Fellowship.</p></lnv:ACKNOWLEDGE><lnv:AUDIT-TRAIL>#ACC#14915487# #dtd510# #X296# #xa03448t#0304386x#01080003#1100106x#2011-06-06T21:58:24# #conversion_date#06/06/2011# #GRANT#</lnv:AUDIT-TRAIL><lnv:REFERENCES-1><lnsm:view type="all"><refpt id="bibl001"/><refpt id="bi0005"/><refpt id="bibl001"/><lnsm:optionhead><h l="1">References</h></lnsm:optionhead><refpt id="bs0005"/><p><lnsm:bib><refpt id="bb0005"/><lk refid="bbb0005">Atkinson et al., 2000</lk> <lnsm:bb>T. Atkinson, S. Cairns, D.A. Cowan, M.J. Danson, D.W. Hough, D.B. Johnson, P.R. Norris, N. Raven, R. Robson, C. Robinson and R.J. Sharp, A microbiological survey of Montserrat island hydrothermal biotopes, <emph typestyle="it">Extremophiles</emph> <emph typestyle="bf">4</emph> (2000), pp. 305&#x2013;313.</lnsm:bb><lnsm:di name="reflinkkey">#Atkinson#2000#305#313#T</lnsm:di></lnsm:bib></p><p><lnsm:bib><refpt id="bb0010"/><lk refid="bbb0010">Baumler et al., 2008</lk> <lnsm:bb>D.J. Baumler, K.-F. Hung, K.C. Jeong and C.W. Kaspar, Molybdate treatment and sulfate starvation decrease ATP and DNA levels in <emph typestyle="it">Ferroplasma acidarmanus</emph>, <emph typestyle="it">Archaea</emph> <emph typestyle="bf">2</emph> (2008), pp. 205&#x2013;209.</lnsm:bb><lnsm:di name="reflinkkey">#Baumler#2008#205#209#D</lnsm:di></lnsm:bib></p><p><lnsm:bib>